  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (such as funds from criminal activities like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This practice is illegal in most jurisdictions around the world, including China.\n\nIn China, money laundering is strictly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China** (passed in 2006 and amended in 2021). The law criminalizes money laundering and imposes severe penalties, including fines and imprisonment, on individuals and entities involved in such activities. Additionally, while gambling is generally illegal in mainland China, using proceeds from gambling to launder money is also punishable under the law.\n\nChina actively collaborates with international organizations and other countries to combat money laundering and other financial crimes, demonstrating its commitment to maintaining a fair and transparent financial system.",
